Cloud computing has transformed the way organizations build, deploy, and maintain software applications. Instead of investing heavily in physical hardware and manually managing servers, businesses now rely on cloud platforms to provide computing resources on demand. Among various cloud service providers, Amazon Web Services (AWS) is one of the most widely adopted platforms because of its extensive range of scalable and reliable cloud services.

Traditional IT infrastructure requires administrators to constantly monitor servers, replace failed hardware, and manually increase server capacity whenever application traffic grows. These manual operations consume time, increase operational expenses, and often result in service interruptions. Even a small hardware failure can affect application availability and customer satisfaction.

To address these challenges, AWS provides several managed services that automate infrastructure management. This project combines services such as Amazon EC2, Elastic Load Balancer, Auto Scaling, and CloudWatch to create a self-healing infrastructure capable of recovering automatically from failures and scaling according to workload demand. The infrastructure continuously monitors system health and responds immediately to failures without requiring human intervention.

This project is important because modern businesses demand applications that remain available 24/7 while handling unpredictable traffic efficiently. By implementing self-healing and auto-scaling capabilities, organizations can achieve higher availability, improved reliability, better customer experience, and reduced infrastructure costs. The project also demonstrates industry best practices for designing fault-tolerant cloud environments and provides practical knowledge of AWS cloud services.
